    </ol></li>
      <li><ol class="list-decimal list-inside space-y-1 text-gray-300 my-2 ml-4">
      <li>The prover sends  <span class="math">\\mathfrak{r}_1 \\leftarrow m_1 + \\mathfrak{c} \\cdot \\mu_1</span> ,  <span class="math">\\mathfrak{r}_2 \\leftarrow r_1 + \\mathfrak{c} \\cdot \\rho_1</span> ,  <span class="math">\\mathfrak{r}_3 \\leftarrow m_2 + \\mathfrak{c} \\cdot \\mu_2</span> ,  <span class="math">\\mathfrak{r}_4 \\leftarrow r_2 + \\mathfrak{c} \\cdot \\rho_2</span> ,  <span class="math">\\mathfrak{r}_5 \\leftarrow r_3 + \\mathfrak{c} \\cdot \\rho_3</span> ,  <span class="math">\\mathfrak{r}_6 \\leftarrow r_4 + \\mathfrak{c} \\cdot \\rho_4</span>  to the verifier.</li>
    </ol></li>
      <li><ol class="list-decimal list-inside space-y-1 text-gray-300 my-2 ml-4">
      <li>The verifier accepts iff  <span class="math">\\mathfrak{i}_1 \\cdot E_t^{\\mathfrak{c}} = \\mathsf{Enc}_{\\mathsf{pkt}}(g^{\\mathfrak{r}_1}; \\mathfrak{r}_2), \\ \\mathfrak{i}_2 \\cdot C_v^{\\mathfrak{c}} = \\mathsf{Com}_h(g^{\\mathfrak{r}_3}; \\mathfrak{r}_4), \\ \\mathsf{and} \\ \\mathfrak{i}_3 \\cdot E_m^{\\mathfrak{c}} = E_t^{\\mathfrak{r}_3} \\cdot \\mathsf{Enc}_{\\mathsf{pkt}}(0; \\mathfrak{r}_5) \\cdot \\mathsf{Enc}_{\\mathsf{pkm}}(0; \\mathfrak{r}_6).</span></li>
    </ol></li>
    </ul>

    <p class="text-gray-300"><strong>Lemma 4.</strong> The above  <span class="math">\\Sigma</span> -protocol is correct and satisfies the properties of special soundness and special honest-verifier zero-knowledge.</p>

    <p class="text-gray-300"><span class="math">\\begin{aligned} &amp;\\textit{Proof.} \\;\\; \\text{CORRECTNESS. Clearly,} \\; \\mathbf{i}_1 \\cdot E_t^{\\mathfrak{c}} = \\text{Enc}_{\\mathsf{pkt}}(g^{m_1}; r_1) \\cdot \\text{Enc}_{\\mathsf{pkt}}(g^{\\mathfrak{c} \\cdot \\mu_1}; \\mathfrak{c} \\cdot \\rho_1) = \\text{Enc}_{\\mathsf{pkt}}(g^{m_1 + \\mathfrak{c} \\cdot \\mu_1}; r_1 + \\mathfrak{c} \\cdot \\rho_1) = \\text{Enc}_{\\mathsf{pkt}}(g^{\\mathfrak{r}_1}; \\mathfrak{r}_2), \\\\ &amp;\\mathsf{i}_2 \\cdot C_v^{\\mathfrak{c}} = \\text{Com}_h(g^{m_2}; r_3) \\cdot \\text{Com}_h(g^{\\mathfrak{c} \\cdot \\mu_2}; \\mathfrak{c} \\cdot \\rho_3) = \\text{Com}_h(g^{\\mathfrak{r}_3}; \\mathfrak{r}_4), \\\\ &amp;\\mathsf{and} \\end{aligned}</span></p>

    <p class="text-gray-300"><span class="math">$\\begin{split} \\mathbf{i}_3 \\cdot E_m^{\\mathfrak{c}} &amp;= E_t^{m_2} \\cdot \\mathsf{Enc}_{\\mathsf{pkt}}(0; r_3) \\cdot \\mathsf{Enc}_{\\mathsf{pkm}}(0; r_4) \\cdot E_t^{\\mathfrak{c} \\cdot \\mu_2} \\cdot \\mathsf{Enc}_{\\mathsf{pkt}}(0; \\mathfrak{c} \\cdot \\rho_3) \\cdot \\mathsf{Enc}_{\\mathsf{pkm}}(0; \\mathfrak{c} \\cdot \\rho_4) \\\\ &amp;= E_t^{m_2 + \\mathfrak{c} \\cdot \\mu_2} \\cdot \\mathsf{Enc}_{\\mathsf{pkt}}(0; r_3 + \\mathfrak{c} \\cdot \\rho_3) \\cdot \\mathsf{Enc}_{\\mathsf{pkm}}(0; r_4 + \\mathfrak{c} \\cdot \\rho_4) \\\\ &amp;= E_t^{\\mathfrak{r}_3} \\cdot \\mathsf{Enc}_{\\mathsf{pkt}}(0; \\mathfrak{r}_5) \\cdot \\mathsf{Enc}_{\\mathsf{pkm}}(0; \\mathfrak{r}_6) \\ . \\end{split}</span>$</p>

    <p class="text-gray-300">SPECIAL SOUNDNESS. First, assume that  <span class="math">\\mathbf{i}_1 \\cdot E_t^{\\mathfrak{c}} = \\operatorname{Enc}_{\\mathsf{pkt}}(g^{\\mathfrak{r}_1}; \\mathfrak{r}_2)</span>  and  <span class="math">\\mathbf{i}_1 \\cdot E_t^{\\mathfrak{c}&#x27;} = \\operatorname{Enc}_{\\mathsf{pkt}}(g^{\\mathfrak{r}_1&#x27;}; \\mathfrak{r}_2&#x27;)</span> , where  <span class="math">\\mathfrak{c} \\neq \\mathfrak{c}&#x27;</span> . Then  <span class="math">E_t^{\\mathfrak{c}-\\mathfrak{c}&#x27;} = \\operatorname{Enc}_{\\mathsf{pkt}}(g^{\\mathfrak{r}_1-\\mathfrak{r}_1&#x27;}; \\mathfrak{r}_2-\\mathfrak{r}_2&#x27;)</span> , and thus  <span class="math">E_t = \\operatorname{Enc}_{\\mathsf{pkt}}(g^{(\\mathfrak{r}_1-\\mathfrak{r}_1&#x27;)/(\\mathfrak{c}-\\mathfrak{c}&#x27;)}; (\\mathfrak{r}_2-\\mathfrak{r}_2&#x27;)/(\\mathfrak{c}-\\mathfrak{c}&#x27;))</span> . Thus, given two accepting views, one can find  <span class="math">\\mu_1 = (\\mathfrak{r}_1-\\mathfrak{r}_1&#x27;)/(\\mathfrak{c}-\\mathfrak{c}&#x27;)</span> , and  <span class="math">\\rho_1 = (\\mathfrak{r}_2-\\mathfrak{r}_2&#x27;)/(\\mathfrak{c}-\\mathfrak{c}&#x27;)</span> , such that  <span class="math">E_t = \\operatorname{Enc}_{\\mathsf{pkt}}(g^{\\mu_1}; \\rho_1)</span> . Second, assume that  <span class="math">\\mathfrak{i}_2 \\cdot C_v^{\\mathfrak{c}} = \\operatorname{Com}_h(g^{\\mathfrak{r}_3}; \\mathfrak{r}_4)</span>  and  <span class="math">\\mathfrak{i}_2 \\cdot C_v^{\\mathfrak{c}&#x27;} = \\operatorname{Com}_h(g^{\\mathfrak{r}_3&#x27;}; \\mathfrak{r}_4&#x27;)</span> . Then  <span class="math">C_v^{\\mathfrak{c}-\\mathfrak{c}&#x27;} = \\operatorname{Com}_h(g^{\\mathfrak{r}_3-\\mathfrak{r}_3&#x27;}; \\mathfrak{r}_4-\\mathfrak{r}_4&#x27;)</span> , or  <span class="math">C_v = \\operatorname{Com}_h(g^{\\mu_2}; \\rho_3)</span>  for  <span class="math">\\mu_2 = (\\mathfrak{r}_3 - \\mathfrak{r}_3&#x27;)/(\\mathfrak{c} - \\mathfrak{c}&#x27;)</span>  and  <span class="math">\\rho_3 = (\\mathfrak{r}_4 - \\mathfrak{r}_4&#x27;)/(\\mathfrak{c}-\\mathfrak{c}&#x27;)</span> .</p>

    <p class="text-gray-300">Third, assume that  <span class="math">\\mathbf{i}_3 \\cdot E_m^{\\mathfrak{c}} = E_t^{\\mathfrak{r}_3} \\cdot \\mathsf{Enc}_{\\mathsf{pkt}}(0;\\mathfrak{r}_5) \\cdot \\mathsf{Enc}_{\\mathsf{pkm}}(0;\\mathfrak{r}_6)</span>  and  <span class="math">\\mathbf{i}_2 \\cdot E_m^{\\mathfrak{c}&#x27;} = E_t^{\\mathfrak{r}&#x27;_3} \\cdot \\mathsf{Enc}_{\\mathsf{pkt}}(0;\\mathfrak{r}&#x27;_5) \\cdot \\mathsf{Enc}_{\\mathsf{pkm}}(0;\\mathfrak{r}&#x27;_6)</span> . Then  <span class="math">E_m^{\\mathfrak{c}-\\mathfrak{c}&#x27;} = E_t^{\\mathfrak{r}_3-\\mathfrak{r}&#x27;_3} \\cdot \\mathsf{Enc}_{\\mathsf{pkt}}(0;\\mathfrak{r}_5-\\mathfrak{r}&#x27;_5) \\cdot \\mathsf{Enc}_{\\mathsf{pkm}}(0;\\mathfrak{r}_6-\\mathfrak{r}&#x27;_6)</span> , or  <span class="math">E_m = E_t^{\\mu_2} \\cdot \\mathsf{Enc}_{\\mathsf{pkt}}(0;(\\mathfrak{r}_5-\\mathfrak{r}&#x27;_5)/(\\mathfrak{c}-\\mathfrak{c}&#x27;)) \\cdot \\mathsf{Enc}_{\\mathsf{pkm}}(0;(\\mathfrak{r}_6-\\mathfrak{r}&#x27;_6)/(\\mathfrak{c}-\\mathfrak{c}&#x27;))</span> . Define  <span class="math">\\rho_3 = (\\mathfrak{r}_5-\\mathfrak{r}&#x27;_5)/(\\mathfrak{c}-\\mathfrak{c}&#x27;)</span>  and  <span class="math">\\rho_4 = (\\mathfrak{r}_6-\\mathfrak{r}&#x27;_6)/(\\mathfrak{c}-\\mathfrak{c}&#x27;)</span> , then  <span class="math">E_m = E_t^{\\mu_2} \\cdot \\mathsf{Enc}_{\\mathsf{pkt}}(0;\\rho_3) \\cdot \\mathsf{Enc}_{\\mathsf{pkm}}(0;\\rho_4)</span>  as needed.</p>

    <p class="text-gray-300">SPECIAL HONEST-VERIFIER ZERO-KNOWLEDGE. The simulator can first choose all values  <span class="math">\\mathfrak{c}</span> ,  <span class="math">\\mathfrak{r}_1,\\ldots,\\mathfrak{r}_6</span>  randomly, and then choose  <span class="math">\\mathfrak{i}_1</span> ,  <span class="math">\\mathfrak{i}_2</span>  and  <span class="math">\\mathfrak{i}_3</span>  such that they satisfy the verification. For example,  <span class="math">\\mathfrak{i}_3\\leftarrow E_m^{-\\mathfrak{c}}\\cdot E_t^{\\mathfrak{r}_3}\\cdot \\operatorname{Enc}_{\\mathsf{pkt}}(0;\\mathfrak{r}_5)\\cdot \\operatorname{Enc}_{\\mathsf{pkm}}(0;\\mathfrak{r}_6)</span> . Clearly, the view created by the simulator is indistinguishable from the view in an actual run, given that the verifier is honest.</p>

    <p class="text-gray-300">Note that in this  <span class="math">\\Sigma</span> -protocol,  <span class="math">\\mathfrak{i}_3=E_t^{m_2}\\cdot(\\mathsf{pkt}^{r_3}\\mathsf{pkm}^{r_4},g^{r_3+r_4})</span> . Thus, the prover has to perform 10 exponentiations. The verifier has to perform 17 exponentiations.</p>

      <h3 id="sec-5.2" class="text-xl font-semibold mt-8">5.2 Implementation of Second Protocol</h3>

    <p class="text-gray-300">From the perspective of implementation, the only substantial difference between the two new code-verification protocols is that in the protocol of Sect. 5, one requires a different NIZK protocol. Thus, in the protocol of the current section, the voter PC executes 16 exponentiations, and signs 1 message. The vote collector executes a signature verification, 17 exponentiations to verify  <span class="math">\\pi</span> , and signs one message. For exponentiations alone, he spends  <span class="math">17 \\cdot 3.56 \\approx 60.52</span>  milliseconds, and thus can handle&mdash;taking into account only time, required for exponentiations&mdash;about  <span class="math">59\\,000</span>  votes per hour. The messenger verifies two signatures, and performs 18 exponentiations, being thus able to handle about  <span class="math">56\\,000</span>  messages per hour, when only counting the exponentiations.</p>

      <h3 id="sec-5.3" class="text-xl font-semibold mt-8">5.3 Security Guarantees of Second Protocol</h3>

    <p class="text-gray-300">Most of the security analysis of Sect. <a href="#page-8-0">4.3</a> apply applies to the protocol of the current section, with one crucial difference. Namely, in the case of a coalition between malicious vote collector and malicious messenger, the coalition does not know the value h<sup>v</sup> = g <sup>x</sup><sup>v</sup> , and thus cannot verify, whether the value y is equal to h AESk1(c) <sup>v</sup> for any fixed value c or not. Thus, in this protocol, coalition of online servers cannot breach voter privacy.</p>

    </section>

    <section id="sec-6" class="mb-10">
      <h2 class="text-2xl font-bold">6 Application to Code Voting</h2>

    <p class="text-gray-300">The code-verification voting setting is similar to that of code voting <a href="#page-11-1">[Cha01]</a>. The main difference is that in codeverification voting, the voters just enter c to the PCs, by using any favorite user interface, while in code voting, the voters enter long random numbers. This makes privacy against malicious voter PCs achievable in the code-voting setting but not in the code-verification setting. However, it was felt in Norway that code-voting-like approaches were inapplicable due to usability concerns. Another important difference is that in code-verification voting, at least as it will be implemented in Norway, support for revoting is mandatory. Nevertheless, the two new codeverification voting protocols are also applicable in the code-voting setting. In a nutshell, in the case of code voting, a similar composition of two pseudorandom functions can be defined to map voter's (pseudorandom) input code to the (pseudorandom) integrity check code. For example, one can assume that the input code of voter v is equal to g &minus;fv(c) , where f<sup>v</sup> is some voter-specific function, unknown to the voter PC. We omit further discussion.</p>

